subSubSection.paragraph:
Polyps. The autozooids are retracted into the coenenchyme, making hemispherical mounds. These mounds are distributed on only one side of the colony (
Fig. 3B, C
) and sometimes make clusters of over four or five (
Figs 3B
, 
4B
). They are denser on the branchlets than on the base of the colony (
Fig. 4A
). They are 
1.46–1.69 mm
in diameter and 
0.47–0.78 mm
high (
Table 2
). Siphonozooids are invisible to the naked eye (
Fig. 7
), forming minute pits 
0.05–0.12 mm
in diameter (
Table 2
), distributed randomly on the both sides (
Fig. 7
).

Color. The dry coenenchyme is red to orange and yellowish on branchlets (
Figs 3–7
). The axis is white (
Fig. 5B
).

The most abundant sclerites are symmetric 8-radiates and double-clubs in most of the specimens, such as NSMT-Co 1717 (
Fig. 9
). However, in 
4 specimens
(NSMT-Co 1722, NSMT-Co 1723, NSMT-Co 1724 and NSMT-Co 1726) asymmetric 6-radiates are most abundant (
Fig. 11
). However, the size of autozooids (
Table 2
) and sclerites (Table 3) are very uniform, and the other characters are also similar. Therefore, we conclude that the differences in % composition of sclerites can be attributed to intraspecific variation.
